  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With the goal of facilitating farmers to transition from simply subsistence agriculture to a surplus production that can be commercially sold, this agriculture project seeks to provide farmers access to improved seeds (maize, sorghum, rice and cassava), mechanized tools (for planting and for processing), and training on association formation and collective marketing.



With this agriculture project the Diocese of Boga seeks to expand upon the Episcopal Relief &amp;amp; Development-supported asset-based church and community mobilization program called &#x201C;Ensemble Nous Pouvons&#x201D; (Together We Can) that has been facilitating church and community members in the diocese to identify and effectively use their existing resources in community-led development initiatives.  Through a process of resource mapping, the diocese and communities members have identified the following existing assets upon which their activities will revolve:

(1) Human assets: farming population, diocesan facilitators and skilled agronomists.

(2) Natural assets: land (individuals&#x2019; as well as 4 000 hectares of the Church), proximity to DRC-Uganda border.

(3) Material assets: farmers&#x2019; tools, Diocesan tractor, transport truck, and warehouses for seed storage, good network of roads for practical access to Bunia and Uganda markets.

(4) Financial/Economic assets: farmers&#x2019; contribution/association membership fee, growing market demand in Bunia and Uganda.

(5) Relational assets: contact with commercial sellers of improved seeds and purchasers of production (i.e., beverage industries in Uganda).

(6) Temporal assets: equatorial climate, regular rains that favor 3 planting cycles/year.

(7) Spiritual assets: Ecumenical faith environment uniting individuals in peace and collective prosperity.</narrative>
  </description>
